{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"eceee546-5738-4341-80af-47b0d387a0f5","content":"Your project doesn't exist in the current directory, but here's how to configure it. Create `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your server.\n- Make sure your server reads from stdin and writes to stdout (standard MCP stdio transport).\n\nIf you've already published the server as a standalone binary, you can point `command` directly at the executable instead:\n\n```json\n\"command\": \"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer\"\n```\n\nOnce saved, restart VS Code or use the **MCP: List Servers** command to verify the server is detected.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c0dfc557-f6c6-4a7b-b5cd-26088930df83","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet. The user is asking for configuration guidance. I can still provide the answer based on my knowledge of how MCP servers work with VS Code and GitHub Copilot agent mode.\n\nFor a C# MCP server using stdio transport, the `mcp.json` configuration would use `dotnet run` to start the server. Let me provide the correct configuration.","outputTokens":370,"requestId":"E045:1C83F4:1091365:11F5D1F:69E74F81"},"id":"106a8921-0ae0-486e-be12-bd51af77fe2a","timestamp":"2026-04-21T10:20:58.419Z","parentId":"7fc3eafe-48d2-4896-a2fc-fc678860104a"}
